full_text: As Andy Applegate, an adjuster with Succeed Insurance, I am working on a claim. There are several exposures associated with this claim. I'm going to work on Exposure 3, the third-party vehicle exposure for Bo Simpson. I will set up a service request to have the vehicle fixed. This service is related to the third-party vehicle exposure. Because we definitely want the car fixed, the request type is quote and perform service. The work will be done by Mike's Auto Detailing Shop. And the work will be done on the shop's premises. The service to be performed is Auto Body Repair. When I click Submit, the service request is added, and the application navigates to the services screen. The service request I created is highlighted in the list, and its details appear below. Some time passes and Mike gives me a quote. I add it to the service request. I enter the relevant details of the quote. I enter the relevant details of the quote. Then I update the quote. The status of the quote is waiting for approval. I approve the quote. More time passes, and the vendor completes the work. I record this on the services page. The vendor sends in an invoice, which matches the quote. I add the invoice to the service request. The status of the invoice is now check created. And the status of the check is awaiting submission. This means that the check, which is well within my authority limits, has been approved and is ready for the payment processing system. This has been done by the STIP feature, which will be discussed later in this lesson. This concludes the services and service requests demonstration. segments.text: As Andy Applegate, an adjuster with Succeed Insurance, I am working on a claim. There are several exposures associated with this claim. I'm going to work on Exposure 3, the third-party vehicle exposure for Bo Simpson. I will set up a service request to have the vehicle fixed.
This service is related to the third-party vehicle exposure. Because we definitely want the car fixed, the request type is quote and perform service.
The work will be done by Mike's Auto Detailing Shop. And the work will be done on the shop's premises.
The service to be performed is Auto Body Repair.
When I click Submit,
the service request is added, and the application navigates to the services screen.
The service request I created is highlighted in the list, and its details appear below.
Some time passes and Mike gives me a quote. I add it to the service request.
I enter the relevant details of the quote.
I enter the relevant details of the quote.
Then I update the quote.
The status of the quote is waiting for approval. I approve the quote.
More time passes, and the vendor completes the work. I record this on the services page.
The vendor sends in an invoice, which matches the quote. I add the invoice to the service request.
The status of the invoice is now check created.
And the status of the check is awaiting submission.
This means that the check, which is well within my authority limits, has been approved and is ready for the payment processing system.
This has been done by the STIP feature, which will be discussed later in this lesson.
This concludes the services and service requests demonstration.
